Drawings made between 1997-2007

Sterne's title for the series of drawings she produced between the mid 1960s and early 1970s, "Baldanders" joins two German words: "bald" meaning soon and "ander" for other or different. As the title suggests, the intricate, undulating lines of the drawings transform as the viewer follows the rhythmic, organic shapes they create. See also: "Lettuces"

Similar to the "baldander" series, this related series of paintings from the 1960s portray a head of lettuce from a worm's point of view. In making each of the Lettuces, Sterne placed raw canvas on the floor and then dripped watered-down acrylic paint on to the surface, allowing the lines to bleed into one another.

Created mostly in the 1960s, Sterne described the inspiration of these works as the sense of cohesion she found in combining two elementally opposing forces. Each new painting presented the challenge of communicating a limitless horizon within a strictly vertical format.

Sterne's machines and "anthropographs" evolved in the late 1940s, inspired by the "surreal" American landscape and New York cityscapes. Eventually, these developed and grew into the "New York" and "Spray Roads" series, when Sterne began to focus more on motion.

After "Memories of Romania", Sterne turned with new eyes to her immediate surroundings. She painted everything from the bathroom and kitchen fixtures in her apartment, to cafe scenes, to the larger city scape. Eventually, after a trip to Vermont in 1947, Sterne became increasingly imaginative, beginning her "anthropographs" (machines).

Called "Patterns of Thought" or alternatively, "Architecture of the Mind," these geometric paintings from the 1980s play between exterior and interior space, portraying symbols loaded with cultural meaning.

Unlike other portraits, which vary in style based on the sitter, Sterne's "Everyone" series uses a level of stylistic uniformity that conjures an anonymous, disembodied crowd of faces. Painted on unstretched, unprimed canvases, the works were installed in her home in 1969, and in the Betty Parsons Gallery in 1970 as a total environment.

For several months in 1976, Sterne placed blank, unstretched canvases on the floor of her main living space, and drew a grid pattern on each. Daily, she filled one square grid with either a quote of her own thought and date. The handwriting in each square alternates consistently between all caps and lower case cursive, creating an over-all checkerboard pattern.

Most severe damage or existing condition has become very advanced. The work is insecure, no longer stable and at great risk. Conservation would be so extensive that the compromising of the artist’s hand should be a concern.

Damages or existing condition are noticeable, if not conspicuous in extent; stability of the work is in question, often great risk is a factor. Requires immediate attention by a conservator to prevent further damage or loss. May include major areas of crackling, delamination, losses, or tears; may not include works with such significant damage conservation would compromise the hand of the artist.

Damage is noticeable and may be of middle or increasing severity of size; not serious but should be monitored, and will require remediation by a conservator. May include minor crackling, delamination, losses, or tears; may not include major areas of delamination and losses.

Existing condition(s) noticeable or identified, but which is relatively unimportant and does not involve risk of loss; should be monitored by a conservator, but may not require remediation. May include dirt/grime, minor abrasions, poor canvas tension; may not include crackling, delamination, tears, or losses.
No noticeable or identified damage, or insignificant damage that may not need immediate attention, and may be simply resolved via light cleaning or re-keying.
Prior condition issues have been professionally treated.
Objects reserved for "core" HSF collection.
Objects reserved for further review; to be considered for educational and charitable use (exhibition, publication, etc.), and considered investment assets available for commercial sale pending review
Sub-category of CLASS B applied to indicate priority works within the CLASS B group that are under consideration for CLASS A status, or of other significance.
Objects reviewed and approved as available for consignment
Objects needing further review before assignment of category

label.description: The spatial or temporal topic of the resource, the spatial applicability of the resource, or the jurisdiction under which the resource is relevant. Spatial topic and spatial applicability may be a named place or a location specified by its geographic coordinates. Temporal topic may be a named period, date, or date range. A jurisdiction may be a named administrative entity or a geographic place to which the resource applies. Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the Thesaurus of Geographic Names [TGN]. Where appropriate, named places or time periods can be used in preference to numeric identifiers such as sets of coordinates or date ranges.
